Policy aimed to return U.S. capitalism to its status quo ante each crash only guaranteed passage straight into the next crash.
The events that trigger each capitalist crash differ as do specific features distinguishing one crash from another.
Thus, monetary policies to try and cope with one capitalist crash helped set in motion responses building to the next crash.
The post-2008 recovery lasted longer than the average such period (four to seven years historically) after a capitalist crash.
Those bipartisan establishment policies respond to the current crash in ways that launch capitalism toward its next crash.